+/*
+ * The wakeup fast path in select_idle_sibling() can return an idle CPU
+ * whose SMT sibling is busy, even when the LLC still advertises a fully
+ * idle core. The busy sibling means such a CPU only delivers a fraction
+ * of a core's capacity. Return true when @cpu is one of those degraded
+ * idle CPUs while a fully idle core is likely available, in which case
+ * the fast path is skipped so select_idle_cpu() can find the idle core
+ * instead.
+ *
+ * Gated behind the default-off SIS_PREFER_CORE feature: with it off the
+ * function short-circuits to a jump-label NOP, leaving only two
+ * predicted-false guard_forced tests on the scan-return paths; no cost
+ * has been observed with the feature off.
+ *
+ * Suppressed on asymmetric-capacity systems: there the fall-through
+ * targets select_idle_capacity(), which is already idle-core-aware via
+ * asym_fits_cpu(), so forcing the fall-through would be redundant.
+ *
+ * The ordering keeps the common case cheap: sched_feat() is a static
+ * branch, and test_idle_cores() is a single read of a mostly
+ * read-shared per-LLC flag that is false whenever the LLC is saturated;
+ * only when it reads true is the sibling mask inspected. Callers must
+ * only evaluate this after @cpu has already been established as idle, so
+ * the saturated fast path does no extra work at all.
+ */
+static inline bool smt_prefer_idle_core(int cpu)
+{
+	if (!sched_feat(SIS_PREFER_CORE))
+		return false;
+	if (sched_asym_cpucap_active())
+		return false;
+	return sched_smt_active() && test_idle_cores(cpu) && !is_core_idle(cpu);
+}
